Given a non-empty string s and a dictionary wordDict containing a list of non-empty words, determine if s can be segmented into a space-separated sequence of one or more dictionary words.

Note:

The same word in the dictionary may be reused multiple times in the segmentation.
You may assume the dictionary does not contain duplicate words.

**And my solution is :**
```
class Solution {
    public boolean wordBreak(String s, List&lt;String&gt; wordDict) {
        Set&lt;String&gt; set = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
        Set&lt;String&gt; failed = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
        Set&lt;String&gt; success = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
        int maxLength = 0;
        int[] letters = new int[256];
        for(String word: wordDict){
            maxLength = Math.max(maxLength,word.length());
            for(int i = 0; i&lt; word.length(); i++){
                letters[word.charAt(i)] = 1;
            }
            set.add(word);
        }
        
        for(int i = 0; i&lt; s.length(); i++){
            if(letters[s.charAt(i)]==0)
                return false;
        }
        return dp(s,set,maxLength,failed,success);
        
    }
    
    public boolean dp(String s, Set&lt;String&gt; set,int max,Set&lt;String&gt; failed, Set&lt;String&gt; success){
        // base case 
        if(set.contains(s)){
            success.add(s);
            return true;
        }
        if(success.contains(s)){
            return true;
        }   // do I have to overload the comperator?

        if(failed.contains(s))
            return false;
        // self call
        for(int i = Math.min(max,s.length())-1; i&gt;=0 ; i--){
            if(set.contains(s.substring(0,i+1))){
                String sub= s.substring(i+1,s.length());
                if(success.contains(sub)||dp(sub,set,max,failed,success)){
                    success.add(s);
                    return true;
                }

            }
        }
        failed.add(s);
        // return
        return false;
    }
}
```
**The basic idea of my solution is** 
1. check if the string can be AWordInTheDict + rest; if so, check if the rest can be the same structure recursively.
2. keep a success set and a failed set to avoid duplicate recursive calls.
